            "text": "al., 1 ethnic minority groups may have a greater risk of infection due to comorbidities. 1 In 51 this letter, we want to emphasize the need to assess racial and ethnic disparities in the COVID-52 19 pandemic and also bring attention to the potential risk of COVID-19 infection in patients with 53 hidradenitis suppurativa (HS). HS is a chronic inflammatory skin condition that 54 disproportionately affects African-Americans 2 and has several comorbidities that are also risk 55 factors for severe COVID-19 infection. 56 Recent studies have shown that comorbidities associated with HS include: smoking 57 history, metabolic syndrome (including hypertension), obesity, cardiovascular complications, 58 hypertriglyceridemia, dyslipidemia, and inflammatory bowel disease. 3 Some of these 59 comorbidities, such as smoking and obesity, have even been implicated as risk factors or 60 pathogenic triggers. In addition to COVID-19 infection disproportionately affecting racial and 61 ethnic minorities, emerging data demonstrates that risk factors for severe COVID-19 infection 62 are strikingly similar to HS comorbidities 3,4 (Figure 1). Obesity, cardiovascular conditions, 63 diabetes, hypertension (or metabolic syndrome in HS), and smoking history are all comorbidities 64 and/or risk factors in both diseases. 3,4 In addition, many patients with HS are treated with 65 various immunomodulators or immunosuppressants and it is still unclear if 66 immunomodulator/immunosuppressant use increases the risk of severe COVID-19 infection. 67 Price et al. recently commented on how immunosuppressant and immunomodulator use in 68 dermatology patients may increase susceptibility, persistence, and possible reactivation of viral 69",
